/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1200/format:webp/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 1200w" type="image/webp" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 600px" /><source srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1200/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg 1200w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 600px" data-testid="og" /><img src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1200/0*BCqLyOHF0Viy8eZZ.jpg" alt="" width="600" height="450" /></picture></div></figure></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div>', 'https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1200/format:webp/0*w4tsieOfQmNScCRU.jpg', 'published', (SELECT id FROM categories WHERE name = 'Painting'), TRUE, 123, '2024-01-15 10:00:00', (SELECT id FROM users WHERE name = 'Oliver King')),
    (UUID(), 'Painting and Sculpture: a Speculative Cultural History', 'This speculative cultural history explores the deep-seated distinctions between painting, sculpture, and ritual practices, rooted in prehistoric religious life. Drawing on Gertrude Levys Gate of Horn, the paper delves into the contrast between painters and sculptors as distinct societal roles, each serving different sacred functions—painters capturing the unseen and the dead, while sculptors and architects focus on life, fertility, and survival. By examining the origins of art forms and their connection to ancient rituals, the essay suggests that the evolution of creative practices reflects broader cultural divisions between those who engage with the spiritual and those who shape the physical world.', '<p><img src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:498/0*uTkmpX1vrhkJ02sQ.jpg" alt="" /></p><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Thoughts pursuant to reading&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gertrude_Rachel_Levy" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Gertrude Levy</a>&rsquo;s&nbsp;<a href="https://archive.org/details/in.gov.ignca.37341/page/n5/mode/2up" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow"><em>Gate of Horn</em></a>&nbsp;(1948; I read the second edition, 1963 ) &mdash; hardly the most up-to-date piece of work, and I&rsquo;m sure it has been superseded in many ways by more recent scholars. But I found it very stimulating, nonetheless. In the words of the American poet&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W._S._Merwin" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">William Merwin</a>:</p><blockquote><p data-selectable-paragraph="">There are aspects of her book which probably influenced my sense of what it means to be human; once read they were never quite forgotten. That is true, in some way, of the whole thrust of her story. It struck me somewhat as&nbsp;<em>The Golden Bough</em>&nbsp;had done but its argument seemed even more immediate and pertinent, closer to the coherence of a work of art. Levy was also a classicist, and part of her story is concerned with the development &mdash; as seen through burial practices, symbols, and maps of return &mdash; of the concept of the individual soul, the person or aspect of a person that might be reborn, that suffered and hoped and was remembered in myths.</p></blockquote><p data-selectable-paragraph="">As the book&rsquo;s Vergilian title suggests, Levy&rsquo;s real interest is in tracing what she considers the deep roots of European religious practice by sketching a possible set of ritualist genealogies from the stone age to the classical period and so into modernity (the work&rsquo;s subtitle is: &lsquo;Religious Conceptions of the Stone Age and Their Influence Upon European Thought&rsquo;). The&nbsp;<em>Aeneid</em>&nbsp;is never far from my thoughts &mdash; that great poem, which I love so deeply, so this is all mill-grist to me.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Still it seems to me some of Levy&rsquo;s most intriguing suggestions get mentioned only in passing, and could do with unpacking and exploring. Here, for instance, is one detail that really hits home for me. It comes out of her comparison between what is known of Stone Age &lsquo;Aurignacian&rsquo; practices and the practices of what, clangingly, she calls &lsquo;modern Primitives&rsquo; (she looks in particular at Australian Aboriginals and Tasmanians, Kalahari Bushmen, Eskimos and a few others).</p><blockquote><p data-selectable-paragraph="">The painters are said to have formed an initiated caste, distinct from that of the sculptors who made rock engravings of the south. They lived, it is stated, chiefly in small caves, while the sculptors used huts grouped round the greater caverns which were their permanent rallying-places. It has also been considered probable that the sculptors followed a more easterly route southwards, leaving traces of their work all the way. If so such migrations might reflect the cultural distinction between those Aurignacians of Central Europe and Russia who inhabited huts and made stone and ivory statuettes, and the cave-dwellers who inaugurated painting in the West.&nbsp;<em>[</em>Levy,&nbsp;<em>Gate of Horn</em>, 31<em>]</em></p></blockquote><p data-selectable-paragraph="">So: caveats (for there are of course many). Maybe this is a local and eccentric distinction. Maybe myth and religion changed radically over the tens of thousands of years between the cave paintings and the modern age (the notion that uncovering the world of prehistoric humanity is thereby uncovering the deep, buried logic of modern humanity is a suspect one in many ways &mdash; though it&rsquo;s also a beguiling one, especially when we want to think about modern-day rituals or mysteries that no longer seem to make sense to us). The remnants of Stone Age art that have survived are unlikely to be representative of the entire culture. Because certain kinds of artefacts are more durable than others, or happen to be in places like deep caves far from erosion or previous discovery does not mean that Stone Age men and women necessarily spent a lot of time in deep caves, or devoted much time to the creation of such artefacts. Maybe these cave rituals, and the artefacts associated with them, were aberrations and most Stone Age religion involved perishable matter in open spaces. We don&rsquo;t, indeed can&rsquo;t, know.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">I am, nonetheless, very struck by this apparent deep-rooted and fundamentally sacral distinction between makers of the 2D image and makers of the 3D fetish: between, that is, the painter and the sculptor. It strikes me as important and even profound that these were not considered separate but related &lsquo;artist-priests&rsquo;, but rather that they were completely distinct and immiscible castes doing radically different things. Maybe.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Add-in a third creative-cultic praxis which, we can be more or less certain figured largely in paleolithic religious life, even though it has of course left no archaeological evidence: music, rhythm and dance. Perhaps the tribe&rsquo;s musicians and dancers group formed a third, distinct priesthood.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">I find myself strangely fascinated by the idea that, at the root of all human culture and art, a fundamentally religious distinction was drawn between&nbsp;<em>those who paint</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>those who sculpt</em>, such that these two kinds of artists belonged to entirely different worlds, with different habitations and modes of living. Because it makes a kind of sense.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">It makes sense to me personally, in part (another reason to be wary of all this, I know) because I see the writer&rsquo;s and the painter&rsquo;s creative praxis as being essentially linked, where I see the sculptor&rsquo;s (and by extension: the architect&rsquo;s, and the engineer&rsquo;s) creative praxis as being in some essential way different to the painter-writer&rsquo;s. This may be because, although I can write well, and can even draw (in my amateur way) to an OK standard, I cannot seem to sculpt, and have no engineering smarts whatsoever. I&rsquo;ve tried sculpting a couple of times, with clay and with wood, without success. It doesn&rsquo;t feel intuitive to me, in the way that making lines and squiggles on a piece of paper, or a screen, does.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Let&rsquo;s assume that ideas from palaeolithic humankind do indeed remain operative today in howsoever subterranean or subconscious a sense.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">I hypothesise, more or less wildly:</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">1. Painting is the ancestor of writing, a genealogy that runs via hieroglyphics to more abstract modes of inscribed symbolism: representing reality by making 2D versions of reality. Sculpture, which begins with the making of cultic or sacred fetish objects, is the initial iteration of all later human plastic arts: making statues and masks, building huts and palaces and temples, making machines, landscaping the world.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">2. These two central human activities derive from radically different origin-points. Painters/writers and sculptors/builders are, in some buried but absolutely vital sense for humanity, radically different sorts of people, serving the gods in radically different ways.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">3. The third crucial manifestation of the palaeolithic religious impulse was ritual dance and performance accompanied by rhythm, music and song. From this developed both the theatre (a religious ritual in ancient Greece that became a widespread secular artform, without ever quite leaving behind its sacred elements: &mdash; sporting events, cinema, TV all have their&nbsp;<em>fans</em>, a word etymologically linked to&nbsp;<em>fane</em>, temple) and the traditions of public religious worship, for instance as practised in Christian churches and Muslim mosques weekly worldwide to this day. Kids at a pop concert, supporters at a political rally, sports-fans in a stadium watching their team play, are all manifestations of a fundamentally religious collectivity, more formally actualised when congregants gather in church, synagogue or mosque. This public and collective mode of being-in-the-faith is spatial and organisational, and so fundamentally theatrical-sculptural.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">4. Dancing is a kind of sculpture, and religion develops as a branch of the sculptural, not the painterly, sacred tradition (hence its tendency to erect bigger and more elaborate architectural spaces to situate worship). There are several important religious traditions that ban the painterly (the making of graven images) from worship altogether. There are none that ban the sculptural-architectural. [<strong>*</strong>There&rsquo;s an obvious issue here, since of the many faiths humans have professed over the last many tens-of-thousands of years the two that eventually swept the world were both religions&nbsp;<em>of the book</em>: and so of words, and writing. But in both cases these faiths&rsquo; relationship to the heritage of painting is complex and contradictory: Christian Puritanism, a phenomenon with several heads, and Islam both ban paintings from their places of worship; personal witness trumps written texts in both traditions; Catholics speak and hear, but do not write-and-read, Confession &hellip; and so on.]</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">5. The world in which palaeolithic humanity lived was a&nbsp;<em>sculptural</em>&nbsp;world: filled with actual, graspable objects. Such was the fundamental reality of life and therefore the logic of whatever transcendent Power(s) was behind life. But there was also an element in Paleolithic life that was not actual and graspable: the dead and their chthonic power. The sacred sculptors of the tribe made fetish objects like the Willendorf Venus to preside over the bringing-into-being of new life. The sacred painters made shadow-images, not real, not graspable, of things of the world to record, and perhaps to fix, the unseen, the chthonic and the dead. It was proper that they did this latter under the ground.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">6. Painted images of animals are post-facto records of successful hunts, made to appease the spirits of the slaughtered animals, and their deity, to ensure that such animals would not withdraw themselves in pique and that therefore hunting could continue. When humans died their remains were buried in the earth; this could not happen with hunted animals, because their remains were eaten and made use of, hence the need to make painterly representations of those creatures. [&lsquo;men are represented very sparsely and very timidly&rsquo; in cave art, Levy notes: &lsquo;in striking contrast to the bold certainty of animal designs&rsquo;.]</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">7. Caves and their sacred arts (that is, painting and, later, writing) were associated with death and the dead; sculpture, architecture and engineering with life and the living. This is a crucial point of difference in understanding the way these two vectors of art signify in the modern age.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">8. Painters and writers are chthons and their proper business is to memorialise and placate the dead. Sculptors, architects and engineers are helioists and spatialists and their proper business is to facilitate the hunt, the gathering of the various collective necessaries of life, and the continuing sexuality and fertility of the tribe.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">9. It&rsquo;s not a coincidence that Plato set his most celebrated allegory in a cave, just as it&rsquo;s not a coincidence he banished the poets from his utopia.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">10. Psychoanalysis is a fundamentally painterly/writerly innovation, the iteration of consciousness as an inner cave. It was and remains a chthonic, morbid and introverted art. (I don&rsquo;t say so to dismiss it. On the contrary: Freud and the post-Freudians seem to me to constitute a profoundly insightful and powerful tradition. But then I am a more-or-less morbid, chthonic, introverted writer-type myself).</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">11. There is less difference between hunters and farmers than perhaps I have previously believed. Hunting is essentially a sacred dance and farming is fundamentally sculptural, but both are above-ground manipulations of space that guarantee the life and continuance &mdash; that is, the future &mdash; of the tribe.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">12. Extraverts should sculpt, build and dance; introverts should write and paint. Extraverts should live in houses, venture into the open, and follow a sunrise-sanctioned easterly route southwards, leaving traces of their work all the way. Introverts may stay in their caves.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div>', 'https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/0*uTkmpX1vrhkJ02sQ.jpg', 'published', (SELECT id FROM categories WHERE name = 'Painting'), FALSE, 89, '2024-02-01 14:00:00', (SELECT id FROM users WHERE name = 'Oliver King')),
    (UUID(),'If she were a piece of art, Id never get tired of looking at her', 'This reflection explores the profound impact of an individual who captivates through not just physical beauty, but through the essence of their being. Describing her as a living piece of art, the author conveys the deep admiration felt every time they encounter her. Her smile, laughter, and graceful movements all come together in a timeless display that draws the observer in, creating an emotional response that transcends the ordinary. The narrative touches on how her presence brings color and life to the world, leaving an enduring impression that lingers long after she is gone. The author contemplates the purity and quiet confidence she embodies, and ultimately, the piece suggests that true love is found in someone who transforms the mundane into the extraordinary by simply being themselves.', '
    <p><img src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*eg0HB0ldUxX5bzSqgFt3vg@2x.jpeg" alt="" /></p>
    <p>That&rsquo;s how I feel every time I see her. It&rsquo;s not just the way she looks, but the way she carries herself, the way she moves through the world.&nbsp;<mark>Every little thing about her catches my attention in a way that makes me want to look closer, to study every detail.</mark>&nbsp;<mark>Like a painting that pulls you in and makes you feel something you can&rsquo;t quite explain, she has that same effect on me.</mark></p>
    <p data-selectable-paragraph="">It&rsquo;s the way her smile lights up a room, the way her eyes seem to hold a thousand stories, the way her laugh fills the air with warmth.&nbsp;<mark>I could spend hours just watching her, not even needing to say anything, just taking in the beauty of her presence.</mark>&nbsp;<mark>There&rsquo;s something about the way she exists that makes the world feel more alive, like everything else fades away when she&rsquo;s around.</mark>&nbsp;<mark>She&rsquo;s not perfect, but it&rsquo;s her imperfections that make her even more captivating.</mark></p>
    <p data-selectable-paragraph="">There&rsquo;s something timeless about the way she moves. It&rsquo;s like watching a work of art in motion, each gesture, each step graceful in its own way.&nbsp;<mark>I&rsquo;ve never seen anyone make something as simple as walking feel so meaningful.</mark>&nbsp;<mark>It&rsquo;s as if every movement of hers is a brushstroke, carefully crafted to tell a story.</mark>&nbsp;<mark>And I could watch that story unfold forever without ever getting bored.</mark></p>
    <p data-selectable-paragraph=""><mark>When I think about her, it&rsquo;s not just about her outer beauty, but the way she makes me feel.</mark>&nbsp;She has this way of making everything seem lighter, more colorful. When she&rsquo;s near, the world feels like it&rsquo;s in full bloom, and I&rsquo;m left in awe of how someone can have such an impact without even trying.&nbsp;<mark>It&rsquo;s a feeling that stays with me long after she&rsquo;s gone, like a lingering piece of art that I can&rsquo;t shake from my mind.</mark></p>
    <p data-selectable-paragraph=""><mark>Sometimes, I wonder if she knows how much of an impression she&rsquo;s left on me.</mark>&nbsp;<mark>I think she might, though.</mark>&nbsp;<mark>There&rsquo;s a quiet confidence about her, like she knows the effect she has, but she doesn&rsquo;t need to flaunt it.</mark>&nbsp;She doesn&rsquo;t need to do anything extra to make me notice her.&nbsp;<mark>She just is, and that&rsquo;s enough.</mark>&nbsp;<mark>It&rsquo;s like she&rsquo;s a masterpiece in its purest form &mdash; something that doesn&rsquo;t need to prove anything because it&rsquo;s already perfect just as it is.</mark></p>
    <p data-selectable-paragraph=""><mark>Maybe that&rsquo;s what love is &mdash; finding someone who you can never quite get enough of, someone who makes the ordinary extraordinary just by being themselves.</mark><mark>She&rsquo;s that to me, a work of art that I could admire forever</mark></p>', 'https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:4800/format:webp/1*eg0HB0ldUxX5bzSqgFt3vg@2x.jpeg ', 'published', (SELECT id FROM categories WHERE name = 'Painting'), TRUE, 123, '2024-01-15 10:00:00', (SELECT id FROM users WHERE name = 'Paul Young')),

    (UUID(), 'BBC TV film on migrant deaths in Greece is like 1840 Turner painting on slaves', 'The BBC documentary Dead Calm: Killing in the Med? raises alarming claims of the Greek coastguard allegedly causing migrant deaths by throwing them into the Mediterranean, evoking parallels with J.M.W. Turners 1840 painting Slavers throwing overboard the Dead and the Dying. This Turner painting, depicting the tragic fate of slaves thrown overboard by a British ships crew in 1781, highlights the brutal exploitation of human lives. The documentary brings the horrific idea of human beings as expendable "cargo" into the 21st century, prompting reflection on the persistence of such inhumanity.', '<p><img src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1278/0*6O54zzkNl2e6vEj7.jpeg" alt="" /></p><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><p data-selectable-paragraph="">When the news was read out on the BBC that the Greek coastguard was alleged to have deliberately caused the deaths of migrants in the Mediterranean, my thoughts immediately went to a Turner painting from 1840.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">The painting is titled Slavers throwing overboard the Dead and the Dying &mdash; Typhon coming on. It&rsquo;s also known as Slave Ship and sometimes, just as Slavers. Now hanging in the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston, the 91x138cm painting, documented an event from 1781. In November that year, more than 130 slaves being taken from Africa to the Americas were thrown overboard by the captain of a British ship called Zong. The &ldquo;cargo&rdquo; was got rid off so that the ship&rsquo;s owners could collect insurance monies.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Now, a new BBC documentary,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m0020ct1#xtor=CS8-1000-%5BEditorialPromo_Box%5D-%5BNewsEditorial_Promo%5D-%5BNewsEditorial_Promo%5D-%5BPS_IPLAYER~N~m0020ct1~P_DeadCalm%5D" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Dead Calm: Killing in the Med?</a>&nbsp;has interviewed eyewitnesses who claim the Greek coastguard had been doing the same with migrants unluckily found in Greek territorial waters. If true, these people too are &ldquo;cargo&rdquo; that must be got rid off.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/c0vv717yvpeo" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">The BBC report reads as follows</a>: &ldquo;&hellip;migrants said they were thrown directly into the sea by the Greek authorities&rdquo;.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">The report quotes a Cameroonian migrant who survived: &ldquo;They started with the [other] Cameroonian. They threw him in the water. The Ivorian man said: &lsquo;Save me, I don&rsquo;t want to die&hellip; and then eventually only his hand was above water, and his body was below. Slowly his hand slipped under, and the water engulfed him&rsquo;.&rdquo;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">The claim that migrants are being thrown overboard to their deaths is explosive and the Greek coastguard has strongly rejected it.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Even so, the echoes of the Turner painting are horrifying. It is appalling to even think that behaviour we thought had been left in the 18th century should feature in the 21st.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">It is horrifying that there should be need for another Turner painting &mdash; albeit, using the modern medium of a TV documentary &mdash; to portray such alleged inhumanity against human beings.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">In fact, the more I think of it, the TV documentary is almost exactly like the Turner painting, which was first exhibited in 1840, an important year for the global anti-slavery movement. The World Anti-Slavery Convention met for the first time in London right around now, in June 1840.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Unlike the BBC documentary, however, the Turner painting has been accused of callousness rather than compassion, of telling an incomplete and cynical story about the treatment of vulnerable human beings.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong><em>I&rsquo;ll explore that next.</em></strong></p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><em>Originally published at&nbsp;</em><a href="https://www.rashmee.com/bbc-tv-film-on-migrant-deaths-in-greece-is-like-1840-turner-painting-on-slaves/" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow"><em>https://www.rashmee.com</em></a></p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div>', 'https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1278/format:webp/0*6O54zzkNl2e6vEj7.jpeg', 'published', (SELECT id FROM categories WHERE name = 'Painting'), FALSE, 89, '2024-02-01 14:00:00', (SELECT id FROM users WHERE name = 'Paul Young')),
    (UUID(), 'Vincent Van Gogh''s Artistic Legacy: A Study of Paintings Sold During His Lifetime', 'Vincent Van Gogh, renowned for his expressive and innovative style, created numerous paintings during his lifetime. This paper investigates the extent to which Van Goghs works were commercially successful during his career. Specifically, it explores the number of paintings he sold, the financial implications of these sales, and the broader implications for his recognition as an artist.','<p><strong><img src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*DG6V2PdpIv4oYy674-eqng.jpeg" alt="" /></strong></p><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Abstract:</strong>&nbsp;Vincent Van Gogh, renowned for his expressive and innovative style, created numerous paintings during his lifetime. This paper investigates the extent to which Van Gogh&rsquo;s works were commercially successful during his career. Specifically, it explores the number of paintings he sold, the financial implications of these sales, and the broader implications for his recognition as an artist.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Vincent Van Gogh was a famous artist known for his unique and emotional style of painting. He created many paintings during his lifetime, but this paper aims to look at how successful he was in selling his artwork. We will investigate how many paintings he sold, how much money he made from these sales, and what impact this had on his reputation as an artist.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Van Gogh&rsquo;s paintings were not always popular during his lifetime, and he struggled to sell many of his works. However, he did manage to sell some paintings, and these sales were important for his financial stability. Selling his artwork allowed him to continue painting and pursuing his passion.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">The number of paintings Van Gogh sold varied, with some pieces selling for higher prices than others. These sales were crucial for his income, as he often relied on the money from selling his paintings to support himself.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Overall, the commercial success of Van Gogh&rsquo;s paintings had a significant impact on his recognition as an artist. While he may not have been widely appreciated during his lifetime, the sales of his artwork helped to establish his legacy as one of the most influential artists in history.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Introduction:</strong>&nbsp;Vincent Van Gogh (1853&ndash;1890) is widely regarded as one of the most influential artists of the 19th century, despite his tumultuous life and modest commercial success during his lifetime. His paintings, characterized by bold colors, dramatic brushwork, and emotional depth, have become iconic representations of Post-Impressionist art. However, Van Gogh&rsquo;s financial struggles and limited recognition during his lifetime raise questions about the extent of his commercial success as an artist.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Vincent Van Gogh, who lived from 1853 to 1890, is seen as a hugely important artist from the 19th century. Even though he faced many challenges in his life and didn&rsquo;t sell many paintings while he was alive, his work has had a massive impact. His paintings are known for their vibrant colors, expressive brushstrokes, and deep emotions, making them stand out as examples of Post-Impressionist art.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Despite his artistic brilliance, Van Gogh faced financial difficulties and didn&rsquo;t receive much recognition during his lifetime. This leads us to wonder just how successful he was as a commercial artist.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Methods:</strong>&nbsp;This study relies on historical records, including sales receipts, correspondence, and documented transactions involving Van Gogh&rsquo;s artworks. Primary sources such as letters to his brother Theo Van Gogh, gallery records, and auction catalogues provide insights into the number of paintings sold by Van Gogh during his career.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">This study delves into Vincent Van Gogh&rsquo;s commercial success by examining historical documents like sales receipts, letters, and records of transactions related to his artworks. Primary sources, including letters exchanged with his brother Theo Van Gogh, gallery archives, and auction listings, offer valuable information on the paintings sold by Van Gogh throughout his artistic journey. These records provide a detailed look at the commercial aspects of Van Gogh&rsquo;s career and shed light on the extent of his success in selling his artwork.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Results:</strong>&nbsp;Van Gogh sold a relatively small number of paintings during his lifetime. Historical records indicate that he sold approximately [insert number here] paintings directly to collectors and through art dealers. The majority of these sales occurred in the last few years of his life when his artistic output peaked, despite his ongoing struggle with mental illness and personal challenges.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Financially, Van Gogh&rsquo;s sales did not provide substantial income during his lifetime. His paintings were often undervalued or misunderstood by contemporary audiences, reflecting the broader challenges faced by avant-garde artists in the late 19th century art market.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Van Gogh&rsquo;s sales during his lifetime were limited, with historical records showing that he sold around [insert number here] paintings directly to collectors and through art dealers. Most of these sales took place in the final years of his life when he was producing a significant amount of artwork, despite battling mental health issues and personal hardships.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Financially, the sales of Van Gogh&rsquo;s paintings did not bring in a substantial income while he was alive. His work was frequently undervalued or not fully appreciated by the audiences of his time, highlighting the struggles that avant-garde artists faced in the late 19th-century art market.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Discussion:</strong>&nbsp;The limited number of paintings sold by Van Gogh contrasts sharply with his posthumous reputation and the market value of his works today. His commercial success was hindered by factors such as his unconventional artistic style, personal struggles, and the nascent state of the art market during his time.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Despite these challenges, Van Gogh&rsquo;s artistic vision and creative output laid the foundation for future artistic movements. His influence on subsequent generations of artists and the enduring popularity of his paintings underscore the discrepancy between commercial success and artistic legacy.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Van Gogh&rsquo;s modest sales of paintings during his lifetime stand in stark contrast to his immense posthumous reputation and the high market value of his works today. His commercial success was limited due to various factors, including his unconventional artistic style, personal challenges, and the underdeveloped nature of the art market in his era.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Despite these obstacles, Van Gogh&rsquo;s artistic vision and prolific output paved the way for future art movements. His impact on later generations of artists and the enduring appeal of his paintings highlight the disparity between commercial success and artistic legacy. Van Gogh&rsquo;s story serves as a powerful example of how an artist&rsquo;s true worth and influence can transcend the constraints of their time.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Conclusion:</strong>&nbsp;Vincent Van Gogh&rsquo;s career as a painter was marked by modest commercial success and significant personal challenges. While he sold only a limited number of paintings during his lifetime, his impact on the art world has been profound and enduring. Today, his works command admiration and record-breaking prices at auctions, highlighting the disconnect between market success and artistic merit during his lifetime.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">This paper contributes to a deeper understanding of Van Gogh&rsquo;s career and underscores the complexities of artistic recognition and commercial success in the 19th century art market.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Vincent Van Gogh&rsquo;s journey as a painter was defined by humble commercial achievements and notable personal struggles. Despite selling a small number of paintings while alive, his influence on the art scene has been profound and lasting. Presently, his artworks are revered and fetch record prices at auctions, emphasizing the disparity between his market success and artistic brilliance during his time.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">This paper adds to the comprehension of Van Gogh&rsquo;s career, emphasizing the intricacies of artistic acknowledgment and commercial triumph in the 19th-century art world. Van Gogh&rsquo;s story serves as a poignant reminder of how true artistic merit can transcend the limitations of commercial success and leave an indelible mark on the world of art.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">1. Van Gogh, Vincent. &ldquo;Letters to Theo Van Gogh.&rdquo; [Include specific publication details if available]</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">2. Van Gogh Museum. &ldquo;Gallery Records and Documentation.&rdquo; [Include specific details of the museum&rsquo;s archives]</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">3. Auction Catalogues from the 19th Century Art Market. [Include specific catalogues or sources used for the study]</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">4. Zemel, Carol. &ldquo;Van Gogh&rsquo;s Progress: Utopia, Modernity, and Late-Nineteenth-Century Art.&rdquo; [Include publication details]</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">5. Naifeh, Steven, and Gregory White Smith. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Life.&rdquo; [Include publication details]</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">6. Pickvance, Ronald. &ldquo;Van Gogh in Arles.&rdquo; [Include publication details]</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">7. Tralbaut, Marc Edo. &ldquo;Vincent Van Gogh: The Complete Works.&rdquo; [Include publication details]</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">8. Metropolitan Museum of Art. &ldquo;Van Gogh&rsquo;s Artistic Legacy.&rdquo; [Include specific details from the museum&rsquo;s collection]</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">9. National Gallery of Art. &ldquo;Van Gogh and the Post-Impressionists.&rdquo; [Include specific details from the gallery&rsquo;s collection]</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">10. Gogh, Theo Van. &ldquo;Correspondence with Vincent Van Gogh.&rdquo; [Include specific publication details if available]</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Keywords</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">1. Vincent, 2. Van Gogh, 3. Artist, 4. Painter, 5. Post-Impressionist, 6. Artwork</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">7. Legacy,8. Commercial Success,9. Sales,10. Influence,11. Mental Health</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">12. Emotional,13. Expression,14. Brushwork,15. Color,16. Art Market,17. Recognition,18. Artistic Vision,19. Personal Struggles,20. Artistic Movement</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Additional Information for Van Gogh</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">1. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Life&rdquo; by Steven Naifeh and Gregory White Smith (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">2. &ldquo;Van Gogh&rsquo;s Progress: Utopia, Modernity, and Late-Nineteenth-Century Art&rdquo; by Carol Zemel (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">3. &ldquo;Van Gogh in Arles&rdquo; by Ronald Pickvance (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">4. &ldquo;Vincent Van Gogh: The Complete Works&rdquo; by Marc Edo Tralbaut (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">5. &ldquo;Van Gogh and the Colors of the Night&rdquo; by Sjraar van Heugten (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">6. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Complete Paintings&rdquo; by Ingo F. Walther and Rainer Metzger (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">7. &ldquo;Van Gogh&rsquo;s Bedrooms&rdquo; by Gloria Groom (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">8. &ldquo;Van Gogh&rsquo;s Ear: The True Story&rdquo; by Bernadette Murphy (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">9. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Life, the Letters, the Complete Paintings&rdquo; by Rainer Metzger (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">10. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Complete Van Gogh&rdquo; by Jan Hulsker (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">11. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Complete Paintings&rdquo; by Taschen (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">12. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Complete Works&rdquo; by Taschen (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">13. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Complete Paintings&rdquo; by Rainer Metzger (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">14. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Complete Paintings&rdquo; by Ingo F. Walther (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">15. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Complete Paintings&rdquo; by Rainer Metzger and Ingo F. Walther (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">16. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Complete Paintings&rdquo; by Rainer Metzger and Taschen (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">17. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Complete Paintings&rdquo; by Rainer Metzger and Ingo F. Walther (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">18. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Complete Paintings&rdquo; by Rainer Metzger and Ingo F. Walther (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">19. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Complete Paintings&rdquo; by Rainer Metzger and Taschen (Book)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">20. &ldquo;Van Gogh: The Complete Paintings&rdquo; by Rainer Metzger and Ingo F. Walther (Book)</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div>', 'https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*DG6V2PdpIv4oYy674-eqng.jpeg', 'published', (SELECT id FROM categories WHERE name = 'Painting'), TRUE, 89, '2024-02-01 14:00:00', (SELECT id FROM users WHERE name = 'Paul Young')),
	(UUID(), 'Forever Young: How Music Can Slow Ageing', 'Music has the potential to slow the ageing process, benefiting both the body and mind. Research shows that music stimulates multiple brain regions, enhancing cognitive function, memory, and emotional well-being. Active engagement, such as playing an instrument, improves neuroplasticity, supporting brain health and combating age-related decline. Passive listening also promotes mental agility and boosts mood, contributing to cognitive longevity. Additionally, music reduces stress and inflammation, benefiting physical health by lowering the risk of chronic diseases. Social music experiences, like singing in choirs or attending live concerts, foster emotional connections and well-being. Ultimately, music offers a powerful tool for healthy ageing, enhancing quality of life across various dimensions.','<div><p><img src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*ZUWuLKg8D9l7fytW9ayHkg.png" alt="A child and an elderly man sitting on a bench together in a park in autumn, both wearing headphones and smiling." /></p></div><div><div><div><div><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><mark>Music has the power to lift our spirits, spark memories, and make us feel alive.</mark>&nbsp;But what if music could do more than just brighten our day? What if it could actually help slow down the ageing process? As it turns out, science is starting to support what many of us have always felt: music isn&rsquo;t just good for the soul, it&rsquo;s good for the body and mind too.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Music lights up nearly all parts of the brain, including the hippocampus and amygdala, which activate emotional responses to music through memory; the limbic system, which governs pleasure, motivation, and reward; and the body&rsquo;s motor system. This makes music the ultimate brain workout, and actually one of the most salient stimuli we can engage with&sup1;.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Emerging research shows that music can play a significant role in healthy ageing, helping us stay mentally sharp, emotionally steady, and even physically fit&sup2;. From enhancing brain health and reducing stress to fostering social connections, the evidence behind music&rsquo;s anti-ageing effects is growing. So, if you&rsquo;ve been looking for a reason to buy those concert tickets or hit play on your favourite playlist, this might just be it.</p><h1 data-selectable-paragraph="">Music and brain health: slowing cognitive decline</h1><h2 data-selectable-paragraph="">The benefits of playing an instrument</h2><p data-selectable-paragraph="">There&rsquo;s an underlying reason why many of us were encouraged &mdash; or pushed &mdash; to learn an instrument at a young age. The concept of neuroplasticity plays a crucial role here, referring to the brain&rsquo;s ability to change and adapt by forming new neural connections. Playing a musical instrument has been shown to boost cognitive abilities by improving communication between the brain&rsquo;s left and right hemispheres&sup3;. This neuroplasticity leads to positive effects on learning, memory, fine motor skills, verbal reasoning, and non-verbal reasoning, ultimately resulting in a more capable brain that can adapt to various situations&sup3;. This is especially relevant as we age, as engaging in music can enhance cognitive resilience, helping to maintain mental sharpness and combat age-related decline.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Music training also strengthens memory retention, which is crucial for older adults dealing with memory loss. Particularly in those with dementia, engaging in music activities has been found to improve cognitive functions such as memory, facilitating the recall of personal memories; as well as overall benefit quality of life through increased well-being and social connectivity⁴. Additionally, the fine motor skills developed through playing an instrument can help maintain dexterity and reduce the risk of falls⁵. By tracking participants over decades, researchers from the University of California discovered that those with musical training as a child demonstrated better in all these cognitive functions, even in their older age⁶. Therefore, encouraging such musical activities may offer a valuable strategy for enhancing quality of life and mitigating some of the challenges associated with ageing.</p><h2 data-selectable-paragraph="">Passive listening and singing</h2><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Don&rsquo;t play an instrument? That works too! Passive music listening also provides significant cognitive benefits. Research indicates that simply listening to music can stimulate brain activity, enhance mood, and improve memory retention⁷. Different genres of music can influence our memory and cognitive abilities in various ways. For example, classical music has been shown to enhance memory and cognitive function &mdash; particularly spatial-temporal reasoning, which involves the mental visualisation of how objects fit together &mdash; an essential skill for problem-solving and decision-making. On the other hand, genres like upbeat pop and jazz can also contribute positively to memory performance by boosting mood and focus. Enhanced emotional states can lead to improved cognitive function, making it easier to retain information. Thus, the type of music we choose to listen to can be a valuable tool for enhancing memory and mental agility as we age⁸.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">One element of life that is key to healthy ageing, is sleep. We all need it. Sleep functions as a restorative process providing time for the brain and body to recover from the day&rsquo;s activities; and when disrupted, it can drive age-related disease and shorten lifespan⁹. Several studies have shown a significant effect of music on improving sleep quality and increasing sleep satisfaction&sup1;⁰. This is attributed to its effect on the stress hormone cortisol, soothing the autonomic nervous system and in turn, making one feel relaxed and ready to sleep with more ease than usual&sup1;&sup1;.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Additionally, singing &mdash; whether alone or in a group &mdash; can further enhance these benefits. Singing has been found to not only enhance verbal skills but also promote mental agility, contributing to better problem-solving abilities&sup1;&sup2;.</p><h1 data-selectable-paragraph="">The impact of music on physical ageing: reducing stress and inflammation</h1><h2 data-selectable-paragraph="">Stress reduction</h2><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Prolonged experiences of stress are related to poor health, triggering inflammation, weaken the immune system, and increase the risk of diseases like heart disease, diabetes, and neurodegenerative conditions &mdash; thus having a detrimental effect of ageing and longevity&sup1;&sup3;. Music, however, offers a non-invasive and effective way to combat this. Numerous studies have shown that listening to music can significantly lower stress and anxiety levels, through reducing cortisol and soothing the nervous system&sup1;⁴.</p><h2 data-selectable-paragraph="">Inflammation, immunity and health conditions</h2><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Music can also have an effect on biological markers that drive ill health. A study published in&nbsp;<em>Psychosomatic Medicine</em>&nbsp;found that music can reduce the production of pro-inflammatory cytokines which are linked to a range of age-related diseases, including cardiovascular conditions and arthritis&sup1;⁵. By reducing these inflammatory markers, music may help lower the risks associated with chronic illnesses that often accompany ageing, such as heart disease and rheumatoid arthritis.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Singing can also serve as a form of physical exercise for the lungs and diaphragm, promoting respiratory health. Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD) is an example of a respiratory condition that affects over 1.2 million people in the UK&sup1;⁶, which calls for new techniques to manage the condition and improve quality of life for those with it. Singing for Lung Health is a group based intervention with the goal of improving the quality of life of people with a chronic lung condition, providing them with ways to manage breathlessness as part of their condition&sup1;⁶.</p><h2 data-selectable-paragraph="">Dancing and movement</h2><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Of course, music makes us want to boogie. And dancing, has a profound positive impact on health and ageing. Movement triggered by music releases dopamine, our &ldquo;feel good&rdquo; hormones &mdash; and endorphins, a natural painkiller &mdash; which reduce stress and promote a sense of well-being&sup1;⁷. Music does also help us&nbsp;<em>want</em>&nbsp;to exercise&sup1;⁸, so that helps to get us moving and reaping those positive cognitive, physical and emotional benefits.</p><h1 data-selectable-paragraph="">Enhancing emotional wellbeing and social connectivity</h1><p data-selectable-paragraph="">As the population ages and the number of older adults increases, finding new ways to enhance their quality of life and well-being has become increasingly important. Depression frequently arises as a reactive symptom in the early stages of dementia, highlighting the connection between emotional health and cognitive functioning&sup1;⁹. Conversely, depression is also recognised as a major risk factor for cognitive decline and the onset of dementia&sup2;⁰. This reciprocal relationship underscores the necessity of addressing emotional well-being to mitigate cognitive decline in ageing populations. And with the general population reporting higher levels of loneliness, more importance should be placed on social connectivity more than ever, in order to combat its negative consequences.</p><h2 data-selectable-paragraph="">Choir participation</h2><p data-selectable-paragraph="">One of music&rsquo;s greatest strengths is its ability to create a sense of community. Whether it&rsquo;s participating in a choir, attending a concert, or simply singing along with friends, communal music experiences foster a deep sense of belonging. Research has shown that participating in group singing, such as in choirs, significantly enhances emotional well-being and social connectivity among older adults. A study found that choir members experience improved cognitive function, reduced feelings of loneliness, and enhanced quality of life overall&sup2;&sup1;. This communal environment, along with the joy and fulfilment derived from singing, can be a powerful antidote to the isolation and emotional challenges many older adults face. Consequently, music-based community programs are on the rise, offering older adults opportunities to engage in these collective experiences. But hey, it&rsquo;s for everyone &mdash; consider joining a local choir to reap all the same benefits, at whatever stage of life you are.</p><h2 data-selectable-paragraph="">Live music, concerts and clubbing</h2><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Live music experiences, such as concerts, festivals, and even clubbing, can have profound effects on emotional and physical well-being. These events offer a space for social interaction, movement, and emotional release, all of which play a role in healthy ageing. Researchers have found that group musical experiences such as concerts, trigger social synchronisation, where attendees&rsquo; physiological responses &mdash; such as heart rates &mdash; align with the rhythm and energy of the music&sup2;&sup2;. This phenomena is known as&nbsp;<em>entrainment</em>. This promotes a feeling of social connectedness and emotional bonding among participants, which is unique to live music events&sup2;&sup3;. Concertgoers often feel a powerful sense of community, bonding over their shared love of the same music. This connection enhances emotional well-being and fosters trust among attendees. Studies indicate that concerts create environments where individuals engage collectively, boosting feelings of belonging and deepening their connection to the music, the artist, and fellow fans&sup2;⁴.</p><h1 data-selectable-paragraph="">The takeaways</h1><p data-selectable-paragraph="">In conclusion, music isn&rsquo;t just a source of selfish joy, it&rsquo;s a tool for enhancing our quality of life as we age. From boosting brain health to reducing stress and inflammation, music engages us on multiple levels, promoting cognitive resilience and emotional well-being. Whether through playing an instrument, just listening, singing, or participating in group music experiences, the benefits are clear. Live concerts and even clubbing provide unique opportunities for social connectivity, fostering a sense of community and shared joy among attendees.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">So, the next time you&rsquo;re contemplating a night out or a karaoke night at home, remember that you&rsquo;re not just having fun &mdash; you&rsquo;re investing in your health and happiness.</p></div></div></div><div><div><div><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Sources:</strong></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup1;&nbsp;<a href="https://magazine.hms.harvard.edu/articles/how-music-resonates-brain#:~:text=Music%20also%20lights%20up%20nearly,and%20the%20bodys%20motor%20system." target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">How Music Resonates in the Brain</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup2;&nbsp;<a href="https://www.nia.nih.gov/news/could-musical-medicine-influence-healthy-aging" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Could &lsquo;musical medicine&rsquo; influence healthy aging? Research highlights by the National Institute on Aging</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup3;&nbsp;<a href="https://fisherpub.sjf.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1187&amp;context=ur#:~:text=Playing%20a%20musical%20instrument%20has,overall%20more%20capable%20brain%20to" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Instruments of Knowledge: Music and the Brain</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">⁴&nbsp;<a href="https://practicalneurology.com/articles/2017-june/music-and-dementia-an-overview#:~:text=Several%20studies%20have%20reported%20that,stimulation%20could%20produce%20this%20effect." target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Music and Dementia: An Overview</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">⁵&nbsp;<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37143214/#:~:text=Playing%20an%20instrument%20promotes%20motor,motor%20tasks%20with%20higher%20acuity." target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Fine motor control improves in older adults after 1 year of piano lessons: Analysis of individual development and its coupling with cognition and brain structure</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">⁶&nbsp;<a href="https://www.bps.org.uk/research-digest/learning-musical-instrument-may-confer-lifelong-cognitive-benefits" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Learning a musical instrument may confer lifelong cognitive benefits</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">⁷&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3741536/" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">The psychological functions of music listening</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">⁸&nbsp;<a href="https://www.connollymusic.com/stringovation/which-genres-of-music-improve-your-memory" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Which Genres Of Music Improve Your Memory</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">⁹&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8658028/" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Sleep and Biological Aging: A Short Review</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup1;⁰&nbsp;<a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0965229921000601" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Effects of music intervention on sleep quality of older adults: A systematic review and meta-analysis</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup1;&sup1;&nbsp;<a href="https://www.sleepfoundation.org/noise-and-sleep/music#:~:text=Music%20has%20been%20shown%20to,to%2080%20beats%20per%20minute." target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Music and Sleep</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup1;&sup2;&nbsp;<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28521542/" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">The association between singing and/or playing a musical instrument and cognitive functions in older adults</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup1;&sup3;&nbsp;<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18282566/" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Central effects of stress hormones in health and disease: Understanding the protective and damaging effects of stress and stress mediators</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup1;⁴&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3734071/" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">The Effect of Music on the Human Stress Response</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup1;⁵&nbsp;<a href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapsychiatry/fullarticle/2766707" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Psychosocial Interventions and Immune System Function: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis of Randomized Clinical Trials</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup1;⁶&nbsp;<a href="https://www.themusicalbreath.com/singing-for-lung-health/" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Singing for Lung Health</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup1;⁷&nbsp;<a href="https://www.essex.ac.uk/blog/posts/2021/06/09/the-benefits-of-music-and-dance-for-health" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">The benefits of music and dance for our physical and mental health</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup1;⁸&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8167645/" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">The Influence of Music Preference on Exercise Responses and Performance: A Review</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup1;⁹&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3039168/" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">The complex relationship between depression and dementia</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup2;⁰&nbsp;<a href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamaneurology/fullarticle/2807208?guestAccessKey=92fcb8b9-ef45-4664-ad89-aff8015b42fb&amp;utm_source=For_The_Media&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=ftm_links&amp;utm_content=tfl&amp;utm_term=072423" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Association of Early-, Middle-, and Late-Life Depression With Incident Dementia in a Danish Cohort</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup2;&sup1;&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7857631/#pone.0245666.ref004" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Beneficial effects of choir singing on cognition and well-being of older adults: Evidence from a cross-sectional study</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup2;&sup2;&nbsp;<a href="https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.2316306121" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Live music stimulates the affective brain and emotionally entrains listeners in real time</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup2;&sup3;&nbsp;<a href="https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/psychology/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2018.02682/full" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">How Live Music Moves Us: Head Movement Differences in Audiences to Live Versus Recorded Music</a></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&sup2;⁴&nbsp;<a href="https://gunnoracle.com/25393/uncategorized/the-psychology-behind-concert-going-music-community-and-social-pressures/" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">The psychology behind concert-going: music, community and social pressures</a></p></div></div></div></div>','https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*ZUWuLKg8D9l7fytW9ayHkg.png', 'published', (SELECT id FROM categories WHERE name = 'Music'), TRUE, 89, '2024-02-01 14:00:00', (SELECT id FROM users WHERE name = 'Mia Clark')),
    (UUID(), 'How a Music Degree Led Me to Master in Strategic Marketing', 'This article explores the unconventional journey of a student transitioning from a BA in Music to an MSc in Strategic Marketing at Imperial College London. The author reflects on the surprise and curiosity from peers upon learning about the background in music, which was focused not on performance but on research, including music psychology, education, politics, and management. The article discusses how the study of music, particularly the intersection of music, power, and societal structures, inspired an interest in marketing. The author highlights the role of gender, recognition, and the marketing of musical figures, leading to a passion for understanding modern business dynamics, branding, and power in marketing. The piece also reflects on the diverse experiences of classmates in the MSc program, underscoring the value of varied perspectives and shared learning. Ultimately, the article illustrates how a background in music can provide a unique and valuable lens for understanding and navigating the world of strategic marketing.', '<div><p><img src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*6h2Ksax6ETr3aMO5M3hIsg@2x.jpeg" alt="" /></p></div><div><div><div><div><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Three weeks ago, I walked into my first day of induction as an MSc in Strategic Marketing student at Imperial College London. The atmosphere was electric. A room full of brilliant minds from all over the world, each with their own unique story. Some older, some younger, some just like me &mdash; eager and ready to dive into this next chapter of our lives. It was a thrilling moment, one of those you just know you&rsquo;ll remember for years to come.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">But the real shocker? That came when I started telling people about my background.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><mark>I had only&nbsp;</mark><mark><em>just graduated with a BA in Music.</em></mark></p><figure><div tabindex="0"><div><picture><source srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 1400w" type="image/webp" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /><source srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" data-testid="og" /><img src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg" alt="" width="700" height="467" /></picture></div></div></figure><p data-selectable-paragraph="">I could see it on their faces &mdash; the widening eyes, the surprised grins.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&ldquo;Wait, what? Music?&rdquo;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">And then came the flood of questions:</p><ul><li data-selectable-paragraph="">&ldquo;Wow, how did you end up here?&rdquo;</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">&ldquo;You went from music to marketing?&rdquo;</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">&ldquo;Why marketing?&rdquo;</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">&ldquo;You did music performance, right?&rdquo;</li></ul><p data-selectable-paragraph="">It didn&rsquo;t take long for me to develop a sort of template answer, something to smooth over those looks of shock that I&rsquo;d inevitably encounter again and again.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">&ldquo;<em>Yes, I studied music</em>,&rdquo; I&rsquo;d begin,</p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><mark>&ldquo;but I was more focused on music research &mdash; things like music psychology, education, politics, and management.</mark>&nbsp;It&rsquo;s fascinating how music intersects with so many different areas, but not many people see it that way.&rdquo;</p></div></div></div><div><div><div><p data-selectable-paragraph="">That usually left them stunned. Most people assume a music degree is all about performance and recitals. And sure, that was a part of it, but only a small piece of the puzzle. I had a dissertation. I studied the deeper meanings behind music, and how it&rsquo;s shaped by &mdash; and shapes &mdash; the world around us.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">And it was one journal, in particular, that flipped a switch for me and got me thinking about marketing. Nancy B. Reich wrote about feminism, social status, and women composers in the 19th century. Back then, men held all the power &mdash; over money, over art, over opportunity. If you were a woman, your chances of being recognized as a serious composer were slim to none, no matter how talented you were. The men in the upper classes got all the training, all the chances to perform and publish, while women stayed home to look after the family. Even if you had talent, the opportunities were almost nonexistent.</p></div></div></div><div><div><div><p data-selectable-paragraph="">And what struck me was&nbsp;<mark><em>how this wasn&rsquo;t just a music issue; it was a marketing one too.</em></mark></p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><mark>Traditional marketing, or what passed for it back then &mdash; newspapers, public recognition &mdash; was only ever aimed at men.</mark>&nbsp;Women were left in the shadows. Take a quick poll today, and everyone knows names like Beethoven and Mozart. But what about Fanny Mendelssohn or Clara Schumann? Few people could even name them.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">This lack of recognition was more than just an oversight. It was a direct result of how society &mdash; and, by extension, marketing &mdash; worked. Music was a symbol of social status and freedom, and only the privileged few (and usually men) had access to that symbol. The way they marketed themselves or their work &mdash; through connections, public appearances, newspaper coverage &mdash;<mark> it was all a game of power and status. And women? They didn&rsquo;t even get a chance to play.</mark></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">This deep dive into the politics of music led me to see how closely it was tied to business, marketing, and societal structures. I found this interrelationship fascinating and, honestly, a bit overlooked. That&rsquo;s what set me on the path to marketing.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">It wasn&rsquo;t just about the notes on the page &mdash; it was about who got to write those notes, who got to perform them, and who got recognized for their work. And&nbsp;<mark>that&rsquo;s when I knew: I wanted to understand more about how these dynamics played out in modern marketing, how branding, recognition, and power structures still shape the world of business today.</mark></p></div></div></div><div><div><div><p data-selectable-paragraph="">When I tell this story, it always gets a &ldquo;wow&rdquo; or two.&nbsp;<mark>But honestly, I&rsquo;ve been equally amazed by the backgrounds of my classmates.</mark>&nbsp;Some have spent years in big corporations, others in startups. Many have years of hands-on experience in marketing roles at multinational companies, and I find myself in awe of what they&rsquo;ve achieved already. There&rsquo;s so much I can learn from them.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">But what excites me most is that we&rsquo;re all bringing something different to the table. I bring a unique perspective, shaped by my background in music, research, and history. They bring practical knowledge, industry insights, and experiences I&rsquo;ve only read about.&nbsp;<mark>Together, we&rsquo;re creating this incredible environment of shared learning and growth.</mark></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">And that&rsquo;s the beauty of it &mdash; our differences are what make us stronger, what make these conversations rich and exciting. It&rsquo;s only the beginning, but I already feel like we&rsquo;re on to something amazing.</p></div></div></div></div>', 'https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*08m4Q4iOwe0HueimBWkI_A@2x.jpeg', 'published', (SELECT id FROM categories WHERE name = 'Music'), FALSE, 89, '2024-02-01 14:00:00', (SELECT id FROM users WHERE name = 'Mia Clark')),
    (UUID(), 'My 2024 Summer Reading & Music Lists', 'This piece presents a curated collection of the authors summer reading and music playlists, showcasing a range of books and songs enjoyed over the season. The summer reading list includes a diverse selection of titles, such as James by Percival Everett, Theres Always This Year by Hanif Abdurraqib, and Of Boys and Men by Richard Reeves, covering topics from personal identity to global crises. The music playlist is equally eclectic, featuring artists across various genres, from A Bar Song (Tipsy) by Shaboozey to 365 by Charli XCX, with a mix of soulful, pop, and hip-hop tracks. The article invites readers to discover new works and sounds, highlighting the authors evolving interests in literature and music while encouraging the sharing of recommendations.', '<div><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><h1 data-selectable-paragraph="">Summer Reading List</h1><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><mark>I&rsquo;ve read some great books over the last few months and wanted to share some of my favorites. Let me know if you have any recommendations for books I should check out!</mark></p><figure><div tabindex="0"><div><picture><source srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 1400w" type="image/webp" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /><source srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" data-testid="og" /><img src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png" alt="" width="700" height="700" /></picture></div></div></figure><ul><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>James &mdash; Percival Everett</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>There&rsquo;s Always This Year: On Basketball and Ascension &mdash; Hanif Abdurraqib</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Everyone Who Is Gone Here: The United States, Central America, and the Making of a Crisis &mdash; Jonathan Blitzer</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Reading Genesis &mdash; Marilynne Robinson</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Headshot &mdash; Rita Bullwinkel</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>The God of the Woods &mdash; Liz Moore</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Beautiful Days &mdash; Zach Williams</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Martyr! &mdash; Kaveh Akbar</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Memory Piece &mdash; Lisa Ko</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>The Ministry of Time &mdash; Kaliane Bradley</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>When the Clock Broke: Con Men, Conspiracists, and How America Cracked Up in the Early 1990s &mdash; John Ganz</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Of Boys and Men: Why the Modern Male Is Struggling, Why It Matters, and What to Do about It &mdash; Richard Reeves</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>The Wide Wide Sea: Imperial Ambition, First Contact and the Fateful Final Voyage of Captain James Cook &mdash; Hampton Sides</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Help Wanted &mdash; Adelle Waldman</strong></li></ul><h1 data-selectable-paragraph="">Summer Music Playlist</h1><p data-selectable-paragraph="">With summer winding down, I wanted to share some songs that I&rsquo;ve been listening to lately &mdash; and it wouldn&rsquo;t be my playlist if it didn&rsquo;t include an eclectic mix. I hope you find something new to listen to!</p><figure><div tabindex="0"><div><picture><source srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*LN6NyhSrVxrC4rMqpNT1aQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*LN6NyhSrVxrC4rMqpNT1aQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*LN6NyhSrVxrC4rMqpNT1aQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*LN6NyhSrVxrC4rMqpNT1aQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*LN6NyhSrVxrC4rMqp