ium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 1400w" type="image/webp" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /><source srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" data-testid="og" /><img src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*LKCI9T5gFinKyi4lhKreAg.png" alt="" width="700" height="701" /></picture></div></div></figure><ul><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>A Bar Song (Tipsy) &mdash; Shaboozey</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>365 &mdash; Charli XCX</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>CHIHIRO &mdash; Billie Eilish</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Love Me JeJe &mdash; Tems</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>I like the way you kiss me &mdash; Artemas</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>MILLION DOLLAR BABY &mdash; Tommy Richman</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>I Can&rsquo;t Even Cry &mdash; Hope Tala</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>No Diggity &mdash; Blackstreet ft. Dr. Dre &amp; Queen Pen</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Charge It &mdash; ENNY</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>O Quarto (Soundtrack Version) &mdash; Carminho</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>What&rsquo;s In the Tea? &mdash; Calimossa</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>I Love the Life I Live, I Live the Life I Love &mdash; Hubert Sumlin &amp; Keith Richards</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Say So &mdash; PJ Morton ft. Jojo</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Why Don&rsquo;t You &mdash; Cleo Sol</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>You&rsquo;ve Really Got a Hold on Me &mdash; The Miracles</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Process &mdash; H.E.R.</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>How Do U Want It &mdash; 2Pac ft. K-Ci &amp; JoJo</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>If You Love Somebody Set Them Free &mdash; Sting</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Unsuffer Me &mdash; Lucinda Williams</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Golden &mdash; Jill Scott</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>(I Can&rsquo;t Get No) Satisfaction &mdash; The Rolling Stones</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>My Best &mdash; Saweetie</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Wednesday Night Prayer Meeting &mdash; Charles Mingus</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Come Away With Me &mdash; Norah Jones</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>The People &mdash; Common</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Don&rsquo;t Cry Baby &mdash; Etta James</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>BAD BOY &mdash; Chris Jedi, Gaby Music &amp; Dei V ft. Anuel AA &amp; Ozuna</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>YAYO &mdash; Rema</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Old Dutch &mdash; Bonny Light Horseman</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>symptom of life &mdash; WILLOW</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>WHISKEY WHISKEY &mdash; Moneybagg Yo ft. Morgan Wallen</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Stargazing &mdash; Myles Smith</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Wanna Be &mdash; GloRilla &amp; Megan Thee Stallion</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Jump &mdash; Tyla, Gunna &amp; Skillibeng</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>PERRO NEGRO &mdash; Bad Bunny &amp; Feid</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Lil Boo Thang &mdash; Paul Russell</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Rebirth Of Slick (Cool Like Dat) &mdash; Digable Planets</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Them Belly Full (But We Hungry) &mdash; Bob Marley and the Wailers</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>One of These Things First &mdash; Nick Drake</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Silvio &mdash; Bob Dylan</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Love Is Everywhere &mdash; Pharoah Sanders</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Where Did Our Love Go &mdash; The Supremes</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Texas Hold &rsquo;Em &mdash; Beyonc&eacute;</strong></li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Someone to Watch Over Me &mdash; Samara Joy ft. Pasquale Grasso</strong></li></ul></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div>', 'https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*mPyz3zii83fvCiafwIeXxQ.png', 'published', (SELECT id FROM categories WHERE name = 'Music'), TRUE, 123, '2024-01-15 10:00:00', (SELECT id FROM users WHERE name = 'Mia Clark')),
    (UUID(), 'Nobody Good Will Let Us Use Their Music!', 'This memo, written by Lara Trump, Co-Chair of the RNC, humorously addresses the ongoing issue of campaign rally music rights and the refusal of numerous prominent artists to allow their songs to be played at rallies. After facing bans from artists like Celine Dion, Neil Young, and the Rolling Stones, Lara Trump proposes a new strategy to use music from the public domain—works with expired copyrights. The memo humorously outlines the new music guidelines for various members of the Trump family and campaign team at rallies, including iconic songs from the early 20th century. This directive highlights the campaigns adaptation to copyright restrictions while poking fun at the situation, using humor and sarcasm to cope with the challenge.','<div><p><img src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*cxLhOWm8q_yINVJG.jpg" alt="" /></p></div><div><p data-selectable-paragraph="">URGENT: New Directive on Campaign Rally Music/Explainer on Public Domain</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">TO: All Remaining Members of Advance, Logistics and Campaign Teams</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">FROM: Lara Trump, Co-Chair of the RNC, Daughter-In-Law of President Donald J. Trump</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Hey Loves &ndash;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">It&rsquo;s me again, your RNC Co-Chair-purely-by-merit Lara T!</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">So, like you, I thought we had finally solved the nagging rally music issue when we played &ldquo;My Heart Will Go On&rdquo; from &ldquo;Titanic&rdquo; last week in the always-pivotal battleground state of Montana. But, alas the folks at Sony Music (Japanese) and Celine Dion (Canadian) feel otherwise and have insisted that we cease.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Honestly, it&rsquo;s just as well as apparently, sometime after that cutie pie Leonardo screams that he is &ldquo;King of the World,&rdquo; apparently the boat hits an iceberg and sinks killing 1500 people including Leo, Billy Zane and Victor Garber (something I really wish research would have flagged beforehand). But that is water under (and I suppose in this case, over) the bridge! Ha-Ha. I know, I&rsquo;m so bad ;)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">But, seriously, leave it to the radical liberals in Hollyweird to ruin a great love story.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><mark>Celine joins Neil Young, the Rolling Stones, Adele, Aerosmith, Rhianna, the Beatles, Earth, Wind &amp; Fire, Eddy Grant, Elton John, Prince, Queen, Pavarotti, Nickelback and several dozen other &ldquo;performers&rdquo; that apparently don&rsquo;t want to Make America Great Again.</mark>&nbsp;I am pretty sure some of those acts are not even U.S. citizens, so I say &ldquo;good riddance.&rdquo; Oh, that reminds me, Green Day also hates us.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">For whatever reason, no good musical &ldquo;artists&rdquo; want us to use their music at our way-larger-than-Kamabla&rsquo;s non-AI&rsquo;d campaign rallies. I guess they are all too woke to see the benefit of having their music played in front of ̶6̶,̶5̶0̶0̶ ̶4̶3̶,̶0̶0̶0̶ 147,804 patriots. And yes, I have heard all of you loud and clear and, TBH, agree that we have all enjoyed enough Kid Rock and Lee Greenwood to last several lifetimes That is why, in order to avoid another embarrassing public ban on music usage, we will now only be using works with expired copyrights that are available in the public domain. According to our lawyers, we can use practically any song as long as it was made before 1929 and nobody can stop us. Not even the wishes of the estates of whoever wrote the things. Amazing, right?!</p><p data-selectable-paragraph=""><strong>Therefore, please adhere to the following song guidelines for main cast member stage entrances at our ginormous rallies going forward:</strong></p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">POTUS Trump Solo: &ldquo;Give My Regards to Broadway&rdquo;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Joint Appearance by POTUS Trump &amp; JD: &ldquo;Camptown Races&rdquo;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">JD Solo: &ldquo;Yes! We Have No Bananas&rdquo;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Melania Solo: (I know. I know. &mdash; just covering all possible scenarios): &ldquo;Jeanie with the Light Brown Hair&rdquo; and/or &ldquo;Ave Maria&rdquo;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Joint Appearance JD &amp; Usha (I wrote &ldquo;possible&rdquo; scenarios): N/A</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Joint Appearance Melania &amp; POTUS Trump: (hey, it could happen): &ldquo;Ain&rsquo;t We Got Fun&rdquo;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Don Jr. Solo: &ldquo;Take Me Out to the Ball Game&rdquo; (he still&nbsp;<em>really</em>&nbsp;wants &ldquo;Cats in the Cradle&rdquo; but the new rules are the rules)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Kimberly G. Solo: &ldquo;Charleston&rdquo; (As per her demand to &ldquo;have something I can really move to&rdquo;)</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Eric Solo: &ldquo;Turkey in the Straw&rdquo;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Joint Appearance Jared and Ivanka (should they deign to grace us all): &ldquo;When the Saints Go Marching In&rdquo;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Mike Pence (in the however unlikely event of &ldquo;October Surprise&rdquo; endorsement and even more improbable diminished fear of being hanged: &ldquo;Old Rugged Cross&rdquo; or &ldquo;Parade of the Wooden Soldiers&rdquo;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Rally Conclusion and Stage Exit: Loop consisting of &ldquo;Pomp and Circumstance,&rdquo; &ldquo;Pack Up Your Troubles in Your Old Kit Bag&rdquo; and &ldquo;Happy Birthday to You&rdquo;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Isn&rsquo;t this going to be so much fun? I&rsquo;ll have printed out playlists of other copyright-free songs that can be played while our supporters are standing for hours in the blazing sun at today&rsquo;s mandatory attendance cabaret show in the atrium. You&rsquo;ll receive your copy once your name has been checked off the attendance list at registration. You won&rsquo;t want to miss today&rsquo;s program. I don&rsquo;t want to spoil the surprise but let&rsquo;s just say my song will go on and there is nothing Celine can do to stop me!</p></div>','https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/0*cxLhOWm8q_yINVJG.jpg', 'published', (SELECT id FROM categories WHERE name = 'Music'), TRUE, 89, '2024-02-01 14:00:00', (SELECT id FROM users WHERE name = 'Nina Lee')),
    (UUID(), 'Basics for Jazz Violin and Life in Music', 'Nora Germain, a millennial jazz violinist and author based in Los Angeles, offers a collection of insights and practical advice in her piece Basics for Jazz Violin and Life in Music. Drawing on 17 years of jazz experience and classical training, she shares valuable perspectives for aspiring jazz musicians, particularly violinists. Germain emphasizes the importance of tone, technique, and self-reliance, urging musicians to understand the harmonic structure of jazz, develop improvisational skills, and trust their own creative instincts. Through her personal journey and interactions with renowned mentors, she underscores the significance of continuous learning, respect for the band, and staying true to ones artistic vision. This document serves as a guide to navigating both the technical and philosophical aspects of jazz, offering quick, bold, and sometimes counterintuitive advice that encourages musicians to trust their abilities, be confident, and never give up.','<div><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><div><p data-selectable-paragraph="">My name is&nbsp;<a href="http://noragermain.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Nora Germain</a>. I&rsquo;m a millennial jazz violinist and author based in Los Angeles, and for those of you who are unfamiliar with the image above, it&rsquo;s a historical document of sorts that many of us have encountered in our early jazz education. It&rsquo;s a list of musical tips from the genius pianist Thelonious Monk entitled, &ldquo;Monk&rsquo;s Advice.&rdquo; It&rsquo;s one of many quirky and luminous documents like it that have inspired and intrigued us, and helped us to keep going.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">Keeping going is an art. I&rsquo;ve written about it in my book&nbsp;<a href="https://www.amazon.com/Go-Surviving-Challenges-Becoming-Artist/dp/B0CYRM524C/ref=monarch_sidesheet_image" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">&ldquo;Go For It: Surviving the Challenges of Becoming an Artist,&rdquo;</a>&nbsp;and played about it on my my most recent album,&nbsp;<a href="https://open.spotify.com/album/0HmthWUd5tQ6WZqaQovs8H" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">&ldquo;Postcards from Violin Mountain.&rdquo;</a>&nbsp;Every day, I get DMs, comments and questions from my followers on&nbsp;<a href="http://instagram.com/nora_germain" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Instagram</a>&nbsp;about how to start improvising, how and why I became a jazz violinist, and what advice I can give to a violinist who wants to become more creative &mdash; in any musical style. I&rsquo;ve done many videos about this on Instagram and also on my&nbsp;<a href="https://www.youtube.com/@NoraGermain" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">YouTube</a>&nbsp;channel over the years, but I decided to write down my own list of pertinent ideas which I call &ldquo;Basics for Jazz Violin and Life in Music.&rdquo;</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">It goes without saying (but sometimes it needs to be repeated) that I have never been a professional classical violinist. I did not learn jazz in a month or in a semester. I have worked on jazz &mdash; the craft, my sound, studying the history and working with mentors &mdash; every day for the last 17 years, and that&rsquo;s after at least 10 beginning years of classical training which I constantly rebelled against. There are no shortcuts to anywhere worth going. Everyone has the right to swing and everyone has a right to play the blues, but you have to put in the work. In &ldquo;jazz years,&rdquo; I&rsquo;ve barely started, and I fully intend to keep getting better. Playing with and learning from truly great musicians, like my mentor&nbsp;<a href="https://youtu.be/xbpnLvROYgk?si=KvHSrR_KN7_KAWDo" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Marshall Hawkins</a>&nbsp;who played bass with Miles Davis; my longtime friend&nbsp;<a href="https://youtube.com/shorts/kzfacI8V1jE?si=8EE1duh2CWhuV1ui" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Jon Batiste</a>&nbsp;who has become a light in the darkness for millions of fans; and guitarist&nbsp;<a href="https://youtu.be/kjVlvr1YpG8?si=oSdBeNi5NSApAYTu" target="_blank" rel="noopener ugc nofollow">Martin Taylor MBE</a>, who worked with Stephane Grappelli for over a decade &mdash; is one way that I ground myself in this work.</p><p data-selectable-paragraph="">This was written in basically a stream of consciousness format, and is designed to give the reader quick, bold, possibly counterintuitive pieces of perspective. It&rsquo;s not a lesson plan, it&rsquo;s probably not for everyone and it&rsquo;s certainly not a complete document. (I&rsquo;m not sure it&rsquo;s possible to ever truly &ldquo;complete&rdquo; anything that comes from the human mind.) Here it is, and I hope it&rsquo;s useful. Never give up, and swing for your lives!!!!!! xo NG</p><h1 data-selectable-paragraph="">Basics for Jazz Violin and Life in Music</h1><ul><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Tone</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Technique ie. Scales, good bow hold, intonation!!! Paramount!!!!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Let bowing happen naturally, don&rsquo;t work it out (1&ndash;3 separate notes in a row, 1&ndash;3 slurred notes in a row)</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Trust the body</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Record yourself and listen carefully</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Hear the band in your mind when you play alone</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Learn the bass lines so you know the chords</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Be able to swing alone ie. don&rsquo;t be dependent on others for the swing feeling or for the form.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Be self sufficient, like every other rhythm section player must be, as well.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Contribute &mdash; don&rsquo;t rely!!!!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Always consciously know what key you&rsquo;re in!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Sing along &mdash; if you can sing it you can play it</li><li data-selectable-paragraph=""><mark>If you can&rsquo;t sing it it means you can&rsquo;t hear it yet!</mark></li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Know the chords &amp; play them in a stable tempo (root position, swing rhythm, or just the triads) so you can internalize the harmonic rhythm</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Know the form. Listen to it by itself. Be able to explain it in basic English.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Hear the melody in your solo and let it gently guide you like the lines on a road</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Don&rsquo;t play licks. That&rsquo;s not creative, or applicable to a song in a different key or time signature. Embellish the melody. That is all you need to solo. (Then go further out!)</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Embellish the melody in your own way and your best licks will come from that!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">You can be the first one to do something. If you&rsquo;re strong enough, it can be you.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Be ready!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">No wasted solos!!!! Not even a wasted chorus!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">The melody is NOT a means to an end. Pretend like the melody IS your only solo.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">There is no need to play faster than people can dance.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Work with people who respect you and who you respect. No exceptions.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">If your mentor is a small thinker, has a poor mindset, or is insecure &mdash; find another.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Don&rsquo;t copy other people&rsquo;s entire solos but do study them if it helps you with your own improvisation; If you learned a lot of solos and you sound bad, work on your tone &amp; time instead. And cultivate life experience.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Don&rsquo;t learn jazz from a book</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Be creative</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Know what the tempo and the feeling is before you start and count it off out loud, even if you&rsquo;re by yourself, so you hear the tempo!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">If you&rsquo;re female, play with conviction. Don&rsquo;t be scared. You have to make them believe this shit!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">They will look at you and think they are being conned or there is a catch. Set them straight. Let them have it!!!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">3 things to be able to jam well on known songs: 1. How vividly/ specifically/ clearly you hear music in your mind (melody, chords, core components of known arrangements), 2. How well and fast you can&nbsp;<em>identify</em>&nbsp;what you are hearing in your head (the specific note names, the form), and 3. How easily can you transfer what you hear to what you play? Technique? Knowing the fingerboard? Phrasing? Doing it in one take with no rehearsal or practice ahead?</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Test right now and don&rsquo;t listen to them first. Do this from memory right here. Can you write a chord chart, or play the melody in one take? (Examples: Twinkle, A Favorite Rock Song, a Favorite Pop Song, a Favorite Disney Song?)</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Embellish the rhythms or the articulation if the notes are too complicated at first.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Notice what&rsquo;s going on in the wider sense. How it feels, who is leading, etc.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Don&rsquo;t just focus on tiny details like #4 in a chord.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">If people express limitations, those belong to them &mdash; not to you!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Other people&rsquo;s failures are other people&rsquo;s failures. Even if you share DNA.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Use the lyrics and paint with them! Like sound effects! Tell the story!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Play like a singer would sing the phrase</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Don&rsquo;t put all your faith in one person or institution</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Beware when meeting your heroes</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Know the words if there are any for context/ tone/ meaning in your solo and lyrics also help with memorization</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Create the wave, don&rsquo;t ride it</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Start with ballads so you have more time to connect everything and hear it move along</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Smile and be confident</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Feel everything on 2 &amp; 4 and keep metronome on those beats</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Listen to great drummers! And big bands! Shout choruses!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Practice agility exercises (Diatonic 7th chords and so on, and make your own)</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Copy phrases through chromatic ii-V-I&rsquo;s, etc.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Always be ready to play in any key, so practice scales and songs in all 12 keys</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">After 20 minutes in Db, D is much easier! Think of Muhammad Ali in the pool!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Use consistent fingerings that make sense ie. think enharmonically so you know what you&rsquo;re really doing! Is it Db or C#? Low 4 or High 3 on G string? Create logical fingerings that are likely to work well and are ringing and make sense</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Picture a scene and play into that</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Listen to the melody or someone else&rsquo;s solo first if you are lost/ don&rsquo;t know the song and it&rsquo;s live. This is something to go on. A clue.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Play for the world &mdash; not your peers or professors or critics or even your family</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Don&rsquo;t over-plan things (order &amp; length of solos) &amp; close the door on potential magic</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Leave space if you get confused &mdash; just pause &amp; listen, or come in on beat 2 or the next bar</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Don&rsquo;t rush. And definitely don&rsquo;t drag!!!!!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Take chances</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Do not be a charlatan and do not get discouraged by charlatans</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Keep your integrity and get right with yourself. When you leave a situation that you know is not right, for any reason, a better opportunity will come, or, you yourself are the better opportunity.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">You can always give yourself a chance. Book your own show. Give yourself the first solo.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Learn in your own way, whatever that is</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Be yourself and don&rsquo;t copy any one person too much</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Respect the band and give everyone a chance</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Know the history, watch documentaries and interviews, read books and do research</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Listen carefully to yourself</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Listen carefully to your bandmates. Empower them to play their best and to feel proud about what they contributed. They need to feel confident and fulfilled. This also makes the leader look very good.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">If it isn&rsquo;t working, do something else. Try not to insist.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Take notes on your favorite recordings/ artists/ performances and specifically list what you like about each one (How they stand? Vibrato? Is it their tone? The drums?) These things will become the things that you yourself will work on/ strive for forever.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">If you like it then it&rsquo;s good and it&rsquo;s right</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Nobody can tell you how to sound or what to play &mdash; that&rsquo;s your decision alone to make!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Play with people you like</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Play music that you like</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Listen to music that you like</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Know the melody really well before you change it and never start something you can&rsquo;t finish</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Listen to many versions of a song, especially versions with different singers (the earlier the better) so you know how the song evolved over time &amp; where you want to go</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Trust yourself and the things that inspire you!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Know your strengths, use those &mdash; but improve your weaker areas too (if you want to!)</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Look at your bandmates!!! Communication is key!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Make sure the band enjoys what they are playing. Feature them on things they really want to play. Try to hire people that you don&rsquo;t need to correct or explain things to.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Take responsibility for what happens when you are the band leader. Even when it&rsquo;s painful. Apologize when necessary. And also say thank you as often as possible.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Get rid of charts asap or don&rsquo;t use them at all unless you want to answer a specific question; Remember many charts are full of errors or small differences anyway</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Apply innate knowledge from other areas of life (cooking, singing, dancing, painting, another instrument)</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Talk to the audience and sincerely thank them always, even if you think you performed poorly (don&rsquo;t insult them a second time by taking them for granted!)</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Be careful who you vouch for because talent isn&rsquo;t everything. It&rsquo;s not an indicator of morality. Endorse the wrong person and you&rsquo;ll look bad, but you&rsquo;ll feel worse!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">If the audience is worried for you or doesn&rsquo;t believe in you/ trust you while you are performing, you cannot hope to give them anything but a refund!!!! Make sure they have faith in you so that they can actually relax and enjoy what they paid to see. Earn their trust. Play well. Be excellent and effortless.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Never be afraid</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Don&rsquo;t be boring</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">When teaching, let people get to know you!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Let them ask you personal questions. Answer them honestly.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Teach the whole person, not just the chords of a song.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">You have to hear someone play before giving any help, because everyone has different strengths and weaknesses and you have to hear where they&rsquo;re coming from first before you can suggest anything specific at all</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Listen carefully and they will tell you what they need. Sometimes people just need to cry.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">A lot of people misuse the word &ldquo;jazz&rdquo; so keep your head together</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Go and hear people that you admire and try to hang out with them or you can email them your videos, etc.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Be honest when describing your accomplishments. Do not ever lie or mislead.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Social media is great for showing people what you&rsquo;re about, what you can do and what you want to do.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Succeeding in the world of form is fun, but that&rsquo;s all it is. It will not &ldquo;save&rdquo; or &ldquo;fix&rdquo; you/ your life/ your family/ your soul.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">A long view is crucial. Keep going.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Dwell in possibility, not negativity.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">It&rsquo;s OK if you want to be a leader or a legend, or you don&rsquo;t fit in with your generation or peers.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Make friends with quality people that you admire in a similar craft or mindset, and be around one another for many years. These friendships are crucial.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Have dignity when you negotiate!!!! Know your value in every situation. Communicate that value.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Don&rsquo;t be around people who feel defeated and hopeless. Have dignity. Have gratitude.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Know when it&rsquo;s time to dig in and fight, and know when it&rsquo;s time to let go and let god.</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Spice up your life!!!!!</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Combine genres and make new arrangements but do it tastefully and with respect &amp; grace</li><li data-selectable-paragraph="">Integrity is everything</li></ul></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div>','https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*BUFg5SmaYhnt7z75oLnBkA.jpeg', 'published', (SELECT id FROM categories WHERE name = 'Music'), TRUE, 123, '2024-01-15 10:00:00', (SELECT id FROM users WHERE name = 'Nina Lee')); 

